---
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const entries = (await getCollection('newsroom')).sort(
  (a, b) => b.data.date.valueOf() - a.data.date.valueOf()
);
const latest = entries[0];

// Extract a preview paragraph: the first body paragraph with real
// substance (skip H1/H2, separators, and the short italic dateline).
// Strip basic markdown emphasis so a preview text node renders cleanly
// without literal asterisks. Falls back to the kicker if extraction
// yields nothing.
let latestExcerpt = '';
if (latest) {
  const body = latest.body ?? '';
  const afterFirstH2 = body.split(/^##\s.+$/m).slice(1).join('\n');
  const paragraphs = afterFirstH2
    .split(/\n\s*\n/)
    .map((p) => p.trim())
    .filter((p) => p.length > 200 && !p.startsWith('#') && !p.startsWith('---'));
  const raw = paragraphs[0] ?? latest.data.kicker;
  latestExcerpt = raw
    .replace(/\*\*([^*]+)\*\*/g, '$1')
    .replace(/\*([^*]+)\*/g, '$1')
    .replace(/_([^_]+)_/g, '$1');
}
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About the Newsroom · America's School Trust Library"
  description="How America's School Trust Library covers what's changing in the trust-lands beat, week by week."
  sourceId="newsroom-about"
>
  <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
    <h1>About the Newsroom</h1>

    <p>
      Each Monday morning, this Newsroom publishes a short, sourced account of what
      changed in school trust lands across the United States during the prior week.
      Once a month, those weekly entries are distilled into an email digest for readers
      who would rather follow the beat in monthly rhythm than weekly.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Newsroom is one of three editorial surfaces in this library, and it has the
      narrowest job. The Reading Room holds the long-form synthesis — the booklet,
      the white papers, the per-state dossiers. The Voices section carries signed
      first-person editorial pieces by named contributors who argue for what trustees,
      courts, and legislators ought to do. The Newsroom does neither. It reports —
      third-person, neutral, sourced — on what those trustees, courts, and legislators
      have <em>already</em> done.
    </p>

    <p>
      That separation is deliberate. The trust-lands beat suffers from a thin
      information environment: state-agency press releases land in obscure corners of
      state-government websites, board-meeting decisions are recorded in minutes that
      never make a news cycle, and litigation milestones move through dockets that no
      general-interest reporter is following. The Newsroom exists to bring those
      fragments into one place each week, identify which of them mattered, and present
      them in a form that a journalist, a legislator, a school-board member, or a
      curious citizen can read in five minutes and act on if they choose.
    </p>

    <h2>What the Newsroom covers</h2>

    <p>The Newsroom watches six categories of source each week:</p>

    <p>
      <strong>State land-management agencies</strong> — the Departments of State Lands
      (or their equivalents) in the thirty-two federal-grant states, and the parallel
      offices that administer state-derived school funds in some of the Original
      Thirteen. New annual reports, board minutes, public-comment dockets, and policy
      announcements all surface here.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>State legislatures</strong> — bill trackers in all fifty states, filtered
      for school-trust, permanent-school-fund, common-school-fund, and trust-lands
      keywords. Most weeks return nothing in any given state; when a bill is introduced
      or moves, the signal is high.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Court dockets and opinions</strong> — state supreme-court opinions in the
      active-litigation states, federal-court filings, courts of appeals dockets where
      school-trust cases are in flight. The litigation in Oregon (lead case
      <em>Coos County 24CV38372</em>; Court of Appeals standing victory January 28,
      2026) is the most actively covered, but every state's docket is monitored.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Regional press</strong> — the Oregonian, the Salt Lake Tribune, the
      Albuquerque Journal, the Casper Star-Tribune, the Lincoln Journal Star, the
      Billings Gazette, and a rotating set of others. Newspapers covering trust-lands
      stories that the agencies have not announced themselves — the press is often
      where a story breaks before the official record catches up.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Academic and policy watchers</strong> — university law schools that track
      trust-lands jurisprudence, regional think tanks (Sightline Institute, Headwaters
      Economics, the Property and Environment Research Center), and the National
      Association of State Trust Lands when its members publish.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Movement signal</strong> — the Voices contributors at Advocates for School
      Trust Lands (ASTL), the Oregon affiliate's case docket, and the National
      Conference of State Legislatures' school-finance pulse.
    </p>

    <p>
      The full source list is published at <code>_tools/newsroom/sources.yaml</code> in
      the library's open repository. Sources are added when they surface items the prior
      list missed; sources are retired when they return three months of silence or
      three months of noise. The list is versioned, so the audit trail of what the
      Newsroom watched on any given week is recoverable.
    </p>

    <h2>Cadence</h2>

    <p>
      <strong>Weekly entries</strong> are published every Monday morning. Each entry
      leads with a one-sentence summary of what mattered that week, followed by three
      to seven sourced items in priority order. Each item carries a brief account of
      what happened, links to its primary source (an agency release, a court order, a
      bill filing), links to any secondary press coverage, and a confidence badge.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Quiet weeks are reported as such.</strong> When a week genuinely passes
      with no significant developments — and quiet weeks happen in this beat — the
      Monday entry says so plainly: <em>"This week, no notable developments. Sources
      surveilled: [list]. Last newsworthy item: [date], [topic]."</em> Padding
      low-grade items into a weekly entry would erode the credibility this Newsroom
      exists to build. A Newsroom that is honest about its quiet weeks is one a reader
      can trust to ring the bell loudly when a major week arrives.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>A monthly digest</strong> distills each month's four weekly entries into
      a single email of roughly 600 to 900 words, sent on the first Monday of the
      following month. The monthly is not a concatenation of the weeklies; it is a
      fresh editorial pass that decides which of the month's items will still matter a
      year from now. Subscription information will appear at the bottom of every
      Newsroom entry once the email service is live.
    </p>

    <h2>Editorial discipline</h2>

    <p>
      Every item in this Newsroom carries a <strong>confidence badge</strong>.
      <em>Verified</em> means the item rests on a primary source that the editorial
      pass directly read — an agency release, a board's published minutes, a court
      order, a bill text. <em>Awaiting Confirmation</em> means the item rests on a
      secondary source (a regional newspaper, a third-party report) and the primary
      source has not yet been located or confirmed. <em>Disclosure Unknown</em> means
      the item involves a closed-session decision or a non-public document where the
      editorial pass cannot independently verify the underlying facts. Items that do
      not meet any of those bars do not appear; rumors wait until they are sourced.
    </p>

    <p>
      Items rated <em>major</em> — those likely to shape the legal or policy landscape
      of school trust lands beyond a single week — are subject to a
      <strong>two-source rule</strong>. They appear only when both a credible
      secondary source and the underlying primary source are available and linked.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Corrections</strong> are made in place, with a dated note appended to the
      bottom of the affected entry: <em>"Correction, [date]: the original version of
      this entry stated [X]; the correct fact is [Y]. Source: [link]."</em> The
      repository's version history preserves the original. No silent edits.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>The Newsroom does not editorialize.</strong> When an item invites a
      sharper take — when a trustee decision deserves criticism, when a legislative
      move deserves applause — the editor flags it as a candidate for the Voices
      section, where signed editorial voice is appropriate. The Newsroom itself
      maintains a neutral encyclopedic-news register. That separation is what allows
      state land departments, legislative staff, and courts to read this Newsroom as
      an evidentiary source rather than an adversarial one.
    </p>

    <h2>How this Newsroom is made</h2>

    <p>
      Each weekly entry begins as an automated surveillance pass over the source list.
      The pass fetches each source, compares it against the prior week's snapshot,
      identifies what has changed, and drafts a candidate summary in the
      encyclopedic-news register. That draft is then reviewed, edited, and signed off
      by a named human editor before publication. No item appears on this site without
      that editorial review.
    </p>

    <p>
      This Newsroom carries a standing disclosure: weekly drafts are generated by an AI
      surveillance pass, and every published entry has been reviewed and edited by a
      named human editor. That disclosure is part of why this Newsroom is trustworthy,
      not a complication of its trustworthiness. The editorial process is rigorous,
      the production model is honest, and a reader can audit either at any time.
    </p>

    <h2>Subscribe</h2>

    <p>
      A monthly email digest will launch in the months ahead. Subscription will be
      free; the list will be modest in size and curated for readers who want a single
      concise account of what changed in school trust lands across the country in the
      prior month. A subscribe link will appear on each Newsroom entry once the digest
      is live.
    </p>

    <h2>Quiet weeks, loud weeks, and the long horizon</h2>

    <p>
      The school trusts have been changing for two centuries; their assets, their
      beneficiaries, and the legal frameworks that govern them have all drifted in
      ways the framers of the 1785 Land Ordinance and the various state Admissions
      Acts could not have foreseen. A weekly Newsroom is an inadequate instrument for
      measuring two centuries of drift. A weekly Newsroom is, however, the right
      instrument for <em>catching the present in the act</em> — for noticing, in real
      time, when a state legislature is about to redirect a permanent school fund,
      when a state supreme court is about to rule on a trustee's fiduciary duty, when
      a Department of State Lands is about to enter a transaction that will deplete
      the corpus.
    </p>

    <p>
      The library is built on the conviction that the schools — present and future —
      are entitled to that level of attention. The Newsroom is one of the surfaces
      through which that attention becomes practical. Read it weekly if you are
      working the beat; read the monthly if you are following from a distance; read
      the Reading Room if you want to understand what the trusts are, why they exist,
      and what they were meant to do.
    </p>

    <hr class="archival-divider" />

    <p class="text-sm text-slate-600">
      <em>Editor: Dave Sullivan, President, Oregon Advocates for School Trust Lands.</em><br />
      <em>Editorial review: Margaret Bird, President, Advocates for School Trust Lands (sample reviewer, monthly).</em><br />
      <em>
        Newsroom drafts are generated by an AI surveillance pass over the source list at
        <code>_tools/newsroom/sources.yaml</code>. Every published entry has been reviewed
        and edited by a named human editor before publication.
      </em>
    </p>

    {latest && (
      <>
        <hr class="archival-divider" />
        <section class="latest-entry">
          <h2>Latest entry</h2>
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
            {latest.data.title}
          </p>
          <p class="kicker"><em>{latest.data.kicker}</em></p>
          <p>{latestExcerpt}</p>
          <p>
            <a href={`/newsroom/${latest.slug}/`}>Read the full entry →</a>
          </p>
        </section>
      </>
    )}
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
